# .trivyignore — reviewed CVE / misconfiguration suppressions for CloudWarden's
# Trivy gate (issue #51 / M13.1). Auto-loaded by Trivy from the repo root.
#
# POLICY: we FIX findings rather than suppress them. The CI gate
# (.github/workflows/ci.yml, `security` job) runs `trivy fs`, `trivy image` and
# `trivy config` with `--severity HIGH,CRITICAL --exit-code 1`; the vuln scans
# also pass `--ignore-unfixed`, so only *fixable* HIGH/CRITICAL findings can ever
# reach this file. Everything fixable is patched at the source (backend/frontend
# Dockerfiles + requirements*.txt); the c7n-pinned cryptography/pyjwt CVEs are
# force-patched via a --no-deps override (issue #58).
#
# HOW TO ADD A SUPPRESSION (must be peer-reviewed in the PR that adds it):
#   1. Put a JUSTIFICATION comment on the line immediately ABOVE the id — why the
#      finding is accepted, the owner, and ideally a re-review/expiry date.
#   2. Then the vulnerability / misconfiguration id on its own line, e.g.:
#
#        # No network exposure in our runtime; upstream fix pending (owner: sec, review 2026-09).
#        CVE-2026-12345
#
# The test backend/tests/test_ci_trivy_config.py enforces that every entry here is
# justified this way.
#
# There are currently NO active suppressions — the gate is clean.
